<subSubSection id="7385489AFFA4F86BFF6730395321511C" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="525" pageId="1" pageNumber="524" type="description">
<paragraph id="3B201B11FFA4F86BFF67303951325240" blockId="1.[178,1086,1310,1596]" lastBlockId="2.[178,1085,218,270]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="525" pageId="1" pageNumber="524">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Body length 
<quantity id="FC67B6F4FFA4F868FDC730385075567A" box="[530,611,1310,1332]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="524" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
; length from anterior margin of head to posterior margin of elytra 
<quantity id="FC67B6F4FFA4F868FE5D301D53CF561F" box="[392,473,1339,1361]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="524" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
. Peculiar body by the general structure, narrow and slender, closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="FC9F6092FFA4F868FEBC307C50635621" authority="BORDONI 2004" authorityName="BORDONI" authorityYear="2004" box="[361,629,1369,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Erymus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="524" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis id="09EBC703FFA4F868FEBC307C53C05621" box="[361,470,1370,1391]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="524">E. minutus</emphasis>
BORDONI 2004
</taxonomicName>
from Borneo, but slightly longer, with more protruding eyes and blackish coloration. Head black, pronotum and abdomen brown black, elytra and antennae brown, legs testaceous. Head (
<figureCitation id="A3A40794FFA4F868FD2830B5512C56E7" box="[765,826,1427,1449]" captionStart="Figs 8-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1194,1214]" captionTargetBox="[310,968,220,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-4@4.[291,972,473,829]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-11: Erymus puphan nov.sp.: head (right half omissed) (8), male genital segment (9), sternite of the same (10), aedeagus (11) (scale: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332455" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332455/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="524">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) of peculiar size, slender in shape than other species of the genus, anteriorly dilated, with very protruding eyes. Surface shiny, with distinct and scattered punctures. Pronotum narrow, narrower and longer than head, with anterior margins very oblique and largely rounded anterior angles. Surface shiny, with dorsal series of 6 very scattered punctures and lateral series of 3 anterior punctures. Elytra very large, longer and wider than pronotum, dilated back- wards, with distinct humeri. Surface shiny, with some series of punctures. Abdomen with fine and dense transversal micro striature and fine punctation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B201B11FFA7F86BFF67343B53045223" blockId="2.[178,1085,285,365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">
Male genital segment and sternite of the same as in 
<figureCitation id="A3A40794FFA7F86BFD05343B5120527D" box="[720,822,285,307]" captionStart="Figs 8-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1194,1214]" captionTargetBox="[310,968,220,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-4@4.[291,972,473,829]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-11: Erymus puphan nov.sp.: head (right half omissed) (8), male genital segment (9), sternite of the same (10), aedeagus (11) (scale: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332455" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332455/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">Figs 9-10</figureCitation>
. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="A3A40794FFA7F86BFC60343B51E9527D" box="[949,1023,285,307]" captionStart="Figs 8-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1194,1214]" captionTargetBox="[310,968,220,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-4@4.[291,972,473,829]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-11: Erymus puphan nov.sp.: head (right half omissed) (8), male genital segment (9), sternite of the same (10), aedeagus (11) (scale: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332455" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332455/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) very tiny (
<quantity id="FC67B6F4FFA7F86BFF3B341C5347521E" box="[238,337,314,336]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="525" unit="mm" value="0.48">0.48 mm</quantity>
long), with long parameres and internal sac with an S-like brown structure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B201B11FFA7F86BFF673458511652DD" blockId="2.[178,768,381,403]" box="[178,768,381,403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">
D i s t r i b u t i o n: Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="E424A5B3FFA7F86BFDAE345850B152DD" box="[635,679,382,403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B201B11FFA7F86BFF6734855360529B" blockId="2.[178,1085,418,469]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">
E t y m o l o g y: The epithet is based on the 
<typeStatus id="E424A5B3FFA7F86BFD7D348550C252F6" box="[680,724,419,440]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">type</typeStatus>
locality, Pu Phan Mountains as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B201B11FFA7F86BFF6734C35321511C" blockId="2.[178,1085,485,594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="525">
